\lim_{x \to -3^-} \frac{2^{x+1} - \frac{1}{4}}{x+3}
\frac{a^{u(x)} - 1}{u(x)} = \ln{a}
\lim_{x \to -3^-} \frac{2^{x+1} - \frac{1}{4}}{x+3} = \lim_{x \to -3^-} \frac{2^{x+1}\frac{2^2}{2^2} - \frac{1}{4}}{x+3} = \lim_{x \to -3^-} \frac{\frac{2^{x+3}}{4} - \frac{1}{4}}{x+3} =
= \frac{1}{4}\lim_{x \to -3^-} \frac{2^{x+3}- 1}{x+3} = \frac{1}{4}\ln{2}
2^{x+1} = \exp((x+1)\cdot\ln2)\\ \frac d{dx}2^{x+1} = \ln 2 \exp((x+1)\cdot \ln2) = 2^{x+1} \cdot \ln 2
\left. \frac d{dx} 2^{x+1} \right|_{x=-3} = 2^{-2} \cdot \ln2 = \frac{\ln 2}4
